export const sections: SectionHtml[] = [
 { "anchor": "opener", "html": "<p>Fifteen material classes in one sentence is the most specific government demand signal in this report. On 2026-03-13 China published the Outline (纲要) of its 15th Five-Year Plan (2026–2030), adopted by the National People's Congress on 2026-03-11; its advanced-materials passage names nine classes for &quot;innovation breakthroughs,&quot; four for &quot;quality upgrading,&quot; and two — superconductors and metamaterials — as frontier materials <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"22\">[22]</sup>. Thirteen of the fifteen map directly onto the nine simulation-blocked classes of Chapters 4–12. This chapter is my map of that alignment: what the plan prioritizes, which instruments fund it, which on-ramps are codified for a foreign entity, and which gates bind. It is a map, not a lobbying document. Statuses are as of 2026-07-17.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s16-1-1", "html": "<p>The plan runs in two documents. The Recommendations, adopted at the Fourth Plenum of the 20th CPC Central Committee on 2025-10-23 and published in full on 2025-10-28, set direction and language <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"378\">[378]</sup>. The Outline, adopted 2026-03-11 and published ~2026-03-13, carries the binding indicators, the project boxes (专栏), and the 109 major engineering projects <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"379\">[379]</sup>. The Recommendations sentence that matters most here orders &quot;extraordinary measures&quot; (超常规措施) under the improved new whole-nation system (新型举国体制) for &quot;decisive breakthroughs&quot; across the whole chain (全链条) in six domains: integrated circuits, industrial machine tools, high-end instruments, basic software, <strong>advanced materials</strong>, and biomanufacturing <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"66\">[66]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"378\">[378]</sup>. I read two things into that placement: advanced materials sit in the chokepoint tier, funded whole-chain from basic research through pilot lines (中试) to first-batch application insurance; and the company the field keeps in that sentence — lithography-class hardware, basic software — prices materials as a sovereignty input, not a commodity.</p>\n<p>This is also the first Chinese five-year plan with AI as its organizing logic rather than a sector line. The Outline devotes a standalone part to intelligent development; secondary analyses counted AI mentions an order of magnitude above any prior plan — a count I could not re-verify against the official text and treat as indicative, though the structural fact is verified <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"380\">[380]</sup>. The operational mandate is explicit: the Recommendations order full implementation of the &quot;AI+&quot; action, &quot;using AI to lead the transformation of the scientific research paradigm&quot; (以人工智能引领科研范式变革); the State Council's AI+ Opinions (国发〔2025〕11号, 2025-08-26) make &quot;AI + science and technology&quot; one of six key actions, with intelligent-application penetration targets above 70% by 2027 and 90% by 2030 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"381\">[381]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"378\">[378]</sup>. A plan that orders a research-paradigm change and funds the compute underneath it is, line for line, the charter document of an AI-for-materials venture.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s16-1-2", "html": "<p>Four quantified indicators frame the demand side <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"379\">[379]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"382\">[382]</sup>: R&amp;D spending growth of at least 7% per year (全社会研发经费投入年均增长7%以上); a binding 17% cut in carbon intensity over the plan period (单位国内生产总值二氧化碳排放累计降低17%), codified by the 2024 carbon dual-control work plan <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"382\">[382]</sup>; non-fossil energy at roughly 25% of consumption, with digital-economy core industries at 12.5% of GDP; and 109 major engineering projects, including the national unified compute network (全国一体化算力网) built under the East-Data-West-Computing program — MIIT put national intelligent compute at about 788 EFLOPS by September 2025 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"383\">[383]</sup>.</p>\n<p>The binding −17% carbon-intensity target plus the 25% non-fossil share is the statutory driver behind every electrification class in this report — HTS cables, SiC/GaN power devices, battery chemistries, hydrogen materials — and the compute-network project is the infrastructure half of the AI+ mandate. The demand pull is written as binding indicators with instrument money attached, which §16.4 itemizes.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s16-2", "html": "<p>Set against Chapter 17's US map, the two systems are near mirror images: the same material classes, the same AI-for-materials bet, opposite instrument styles. Chapter 13 identified the overlap; Table 16.1 aligns it domain by domain so Chapter 17 can cross-reference it row by row.</p>\n<p><strong>Table 16.1 — CN/US mirror map of priority domains and instruments (statuses as of 2026-07-17).</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Priority domain</th>\n<th>CN instrument (15FYP)</th>\n<th>US instrument</th>\n<th>Gate</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>AI-for-science research paradigm</td>\n<td>&quot;AI+&quot; action (国发〔2025〕11号) + standalone Outline AI part <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"381\">[381]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"378\">[378]</sup></td>\n<td>Genesis Mission (EO 14363) + $293M FOA <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"25\">[25]</sup></td>\n<td>AI-chip export controls; Nvidia's China share &quot;95%→0%&quot; <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"384\">[384]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Advanced-materials basic research</td>\n<td>&quot;Extraordinary measures&quot; whole-chain funding; NSFC ¥39.46bn 2025 budget <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"378\">[378]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"385\">[385]</sup></td>\n<td>CMEI critical-minerals FOAs (<span class=\"math\">$69M Accelerator; $</span>45.7M FOA-3105) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"386\">[386]</sup></td>\n<td>Foreign-risk screening on US applications; entity-list exposure <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"387\">[387]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Critical minerals and magnets</td>\n<td>Rare-earth upgrade tier + quota and export-control architecture <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"22\">[22]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"38\">[38]</sup></td>\n<td>USGS 60-mineral list (Nov 2025); MAGNITO <span class=\"math\">$20M NOFO within a ~$</span>72M AI-magnet effort (program total single-sourced) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"24\">[24]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"57\">[57]</sup></td>\n<td>October-package suspension lapses 2026-11-10 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"388\">[388]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Fusion energy</td>\n<td>BEST 2027 + Hefei &quot;trillion-yuan fusion city&quot; <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"389\">[389]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"321\">[321]</sup></td>\n<td>Milestone-based fusion program, &gt;$350M in private capital <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"48\">[48]</sup></td>\n<td>Dual-use sensitivity; no 14 MeV test source until ~2034 (Ch10)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Semiconductors and UHP metals</td>\n<td>Big Fund III (¥344bn); ICs first in the &quot;extraordinary measures&quot; sentence <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"390\">[390]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"378\">[378]</sup></td>\n<td>TRACE-Ga ($5.4M); Accelerator Topic 2 (Ga/GaN/Ge/SiC) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"386\">[386]</sup></td>\n<td>Export-control nexus on both sides <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"384\">[384]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hydrogen and storage demand pull</td>\n<td>2 Mt/yr renewable hydrogen by 2030 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"236\">[236]</sup></td>\n<td>Hydrogen-hub cancellations ruled illegal 2026-01-12; appeals pending <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"238\">[238]</sup></td>\n<td>US program continuity risk</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>The mirror shows three things. The domains are symmetric — every Chinese row has a US counterpart, two systems pricing the same chokepoints. The instruments are asymmetric — Beijing works through plan-anchored guidance funds, provincial co-funding, procurement pull, and quota-and-control architecture; Washington through competitive funding opportunities, equity and price floors, and statutory lists. And the gates differ in kind: China's binding gate is a date written into a suspension (2026-11-10); America's is program continuity written into litigation. Note what both sides leave unfunded: each pays for demand and deployment of exactly the simulation-hard classes of Chapters 4–12, and neither funds the error audit those classes are gated on. I draw no competition narrative from the symmetry; it is a demand signal for the same missing capability — validated prediction — and that capability is small enough for an independent lab to matter in.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s16-3-1", "html": "<p>The Outline's advanced-materials sentence reads, verbatim <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"22\">[22]</sup>:</p>\n<p>「加快高端特殊钢、高品质高温合金、超高纯金属、先进陶瓷、高纯石英材料、生物基材料、先进高分子材料、高性能纤维及复合材料、结构功能一体化材料等创新突破，推进稀土功能材料、稀有金属材料、超硬材料、轻质高强合金等提质升级，加强超导材料、超材料等前沿材料研究应用。」</p>\n<p>&quot;Accelerate innovation breakthroughs in high-end special steels, high-quality superalloys, ultra-high-purity metals, advanced ceramics, high-purity quartz, biobased materials, advanced polymers, high-performance fibers and composites, and structure–function integrated materials; advance the quality upgrading of rare-earth functional materials, rare metals, superhard materials, and light high-strength alloys; strengthen frontier-materials research and application in superconductors and metamaterials.&quot; I quote the sentence in full because precision is the point: program staff read for their own lines, and the three verbs — 创新突破 (breakthrough), 提质升级 (upgrade), 前沿研究应用 (frontier research and application) — set three distinct funding postures.</p>\n<p><strong>Table 16.2 — The 15FYP advanced-materials sentence (verbatim) mapped to this report's classes (as of 2026-07-17).</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>15FYP line item (verbatim)</th>\n<th>Tier (verb)</th>\n<th>Report class(es) it names</th>\n<th>Chapter</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>高端特殊钢 high-end special steels</td>\n<td>Breakthrough</td>\n<td>HEAs/superalloys; fusion RAFM steels</td>\n<td>Ch6, Ch10</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>高品质高温合金 high-quality superalloys</td>\n<td>Breakthrough</td>\n<td>HEAs/superalloys (γ/γ′ design)</td>\n<td>Ch6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>超高纯金属 ultra-high-purity metals</td>\n<td>Breakthrough</td>\n<td>WBG-semiconductor process chain (adjacent)</td>\n<td>Ch12</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>先进陶瓷 advanced ceramics</td>\n<td>Breakthrough</td>\n<td>Fusion/nuclear ceramics (W, SiC, Li-ceramics)</td>\n<td>Ch10</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>高纯石英材料 high-purity quartz</td>\n<td>Breakthrough</td>\n<td>Semiconductor-process chain (adjacent)</td>\n<td>Ch12</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>生物基材料 biobased materials</td>\n<td>Breakthrough</td>\n<td>— outside this report's nine classes</td>\n<td>—</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>先进高分子材料 advanced polymers</td>\n<td>Breakthrough</td>\n<td>Porous frameworks (organic-framework adjacency)</td>\n<td>Ch11</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>高性能纤维及复合材料 high-performance fibers and composites</td>\n<td>Breakthrough</td>\n<td>Fusion/nuclear composites; conductors (adjacent)</td>\n<td>Ch10, Ch12</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>结构功能一体化材料 structure–function integrated materials</td>\n<td>Breakthrough</td>\n<td>Cross-cutting: HEAs, fusion structures</td>\n<td>Ch6, Ch10</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>稀土功能材料 rare-earth functional materials</td>\n<td>Upgrade</td>\n<td>Magnets; REBCO superconductors</td>\n<td>Ch9, Ch4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>稀有金属材料 rare metals</td>\n<td>Upgrade</td>\n<td>WBG semiconductors (Ga/Ge); fusion refractories (W/Ta)</td>\n<td>Ch12, Ch10</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>超硬材料 superhard materials</td>\n<td>Upgrade</td>\n<td>WBG: diamond, c-BN</td>\n<td>Ch12</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>轻质高强合金 light high-strength alloys</td>\n<td>Upgrade</td>\n<td>HEAs and alloy-disorder methods</td>\n<td>Ch6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>超导材料 superconducting materials</td>\n<td>Frontier</td>\n<td>Superconductors; fusion magnets</td>\n<td>Ch4, Ch10</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>超材料 metamaterials</td>\n<td>Frontier</td>\n<td>— no dedicated class; noted in Ch4's policy hooks</td>\n<td>—</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Thirteen of the fifteen lines map onto Chapters 4–12; the exceptions are biobased materials and metamaterials, which this report does not treat as classes. Every mapped line is simulation-hard in the sense those chapters document: γ/γ′ superalloy design, purification thermodynamics, ceramic sintering, percolative composites, finite-temperature 4f anisotropy, superconductors with no ab initio route to Tc. The tier verbs carry funding meaning: the breakthrough tier gets whole-chain &quot;extraordinary measures&quot; money; the upgrade tier funds incumbents where China already leads — Trivium's rendering confirms the posture, &quot;continuously strengthening competitive advantages in rare earths, rare metals, and superhard materials&quot; <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"38\">[38]</sup>; the frontier tier gets patient research money. Provincial outlines extend the list — Guangdong pairs superconductors and metamaterials with AI-accelerated R&amp;D <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"391\">[391]</sup>; Guangzhou's frontier-materials box adds high-entropy alloys, single- and double-wall carbon nanotubes, 2D semiconductors, aerogels, quantum dots, graphene, and advanced 3D-printing materials <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"32\">[32]</sup>. For a venture choosing classes, the sentence functions as a procurement forecast: these are the fifteen shelves on which Chinese program money will look for products.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s16-4-1", "html": "<p>The National Natural Science Foundation (NSFC) disclosed a 2025 departmental budget of ≈¥39.458bn (一般公共预算拨款支出预算394.58亿元) and reported funding more than ¥37bn of projects in 2025; the relevant panels for materials simulation are Engineering and Materials (E) and Interdisciplinary Science (codes T01–T04) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"385\">[385]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"392\">[392]</sup>. Its joint funds co-fund with local governments at 1:3 and with enterprises at 1:4 — integration projects near ¥12m — and a 2025 pilot extends the vehicle to private enterprises <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"393\">[393]</sup>. Above the grant layer sit two national equity instruments. The National Venture Capital Guidance Fund (国家创业投资引导基金), announced 2025-03-06, totals ¥1tn with a 20-year life, seeded by ¥100bn of special-treasury-bond money and deployed through three regional funds under a mandate to &quot;invest early, small, long-term, and in hard tech&quot; <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"23\">[23]</sup>. The National AI Industry Investment Fund, established 2025-01-17 under MIIT and the Ministry of Finance, totals ¥60.06bn over a 13-year life with Big Fund III as sole LP; it invests across compute, algorithms, data, and applications, and had made its first chip investment by February 2026 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"394\">[394]</sup>. Its LP — Big Fund III (¥344bn registered, 2024-05) — targets lithography, EDA, HBM, and advanced packaging, making IC materials (photoresists, high-purity precursors, low-k dielectrics) a funded adjacency under the same &quot;extraordinary measures&quot; sentence <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"390\">[390]</sup>.</p>\n<p>The provincial stack is specific. Beijing's &quot;AI + New Materials&quot; action plan (京科材发〔2025〕27号) targets a new-generation large atom model, ten-plus vertical models, fifteen benchmark products, and five to eight unicorns by 2027, alongside a ¥10bn new-materials fund launched in June 2024 — headline sizes verified, disbursement pace undisclosed, so I treat them as commitments of direction rather than deployed capital <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"395\">[395]</sup>. Guangzhou operates a ¥150bn industry mother fund plus a ¥50bn venture mother fund, with district new-materials funds below them — the same hedge applies <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"396\">[396]</sup>. Shanghai combines the Xuhui-domiciled AI fund, Shanghai AI Laboratory's AI4S &quot;Climber&quot; (攀登者) program, and a future-industry plan naming high-end membranes, composites including aero-engine superalloys, and non-silicon chip materials <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"397\">[397]</sup>. The valley-of-death instruments complete the chain: a national guide targets roughly 300 local pilot (中试) platforms by 2027, and the first-batch (首批次) application-insurance catalog covers some 299 materials, de-risking downstream adoption <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"398\">[398]</sup>.</p>\n<p><strong>Table 16.3 — China funding and access instruments relevant to a computational-materials venture (statuses as of 2026-07-17).</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Instrument</th>\n<th>Scale (¥)</th>\n<th>Administrator</th>\n<th>Foreign-entity access route</th>\n<th>Window/deadline</th>\n<th>Status as of 2026-07-17</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>NSFC grant programs</td>\n<td>¥39.46bn 2025 budget; &gt;¥37bn funded <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"385\">[385]</sup></td>\n<td>NSFC</td>\n<td>RFIS: ¥200k/400k/800k per year, 1–2 yr, for foreign PIs at PRC institutions; E and T01–T04 panels <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"392\">[392]</sup></td>\n<td>Annual calls</td>\n<td>Active; NSFC's own 15FYP plan drafted late 2025 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"385\">[385]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>NSFC joint funds</td>\n<td>1:3 regional / 1:4 enterprise matching; integration projects ~¥12m <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"393\">[393]</sup></td>\n<td>NSFC + co-funders</td>\n<td>China-registered enterprises, incl. foreign-invested, co-fund to steer basic research <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"393\">[393]</sup></td>\n<td>Annual guides</td>\n<td>Active; 2025 private-enterprise pilot <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"393\">[393]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>National VC Guidance Fund</td>\n<td>¥1tn total; 20-yr life; ¥100bn fiscal seed <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"23\">[23]</sup></td>\n<td>NDRC / State Council</td>\n<td>Regional sub-funds (Jing-Jin-Ji, Yangtze Delta, GBA) at portfolio level</td>\n<td>Rolling</td>\n<td>Announced 2025-03-06; deploying <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"23\">[23]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>National AI Industry Investment Fund</td>\n<td>¥60.06bn; 13-yr life <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"394\">[394]</sup></td>\n<td>MIIT + MOF (manager 国智投)</td>\n<td>AI-for-science qualifies as &quot;algorithm + empowered application&quot;; domiciled Shanghai Xuhui</td>\n<td>Rolling</td>\n<td>Established 2025-01-17; first investments by Feb 2026 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"394\">[394]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Beijing &quot;AI+New Materials&quot; plan + fund</td>\n<td>¥10bn fund (2024-06); plan targets to 2027 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"395\">[395]</sup></td>\n<td>Beijing Municipal S&amp;T Commission</td>\n<td>揭榜挂帅 open competition; municipal fund</td>\n<td>2025–2027 plan window</td>\n<td>Active; disbursement pace undisclosed <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"395\">[395]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Guangzhou mother funds</td>\n<td>¥150bn industry + ¥50bn VC <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"396\">[396]</sup></td>\n<td>Guangzhou</td>\n<td>District-level new-materials funds</td>\n<td>Rolling</td>\n<td>Active; deployment pace undisclosed <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"396\">[396]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Shenzhen compute vouchers (训力券)</td>\n<td>≤¥500m/yr budget; ≤50% of contract (60% startups), cap ¥10m <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"399\">[399]</sup></td>\n<td>Shenzhen (MIIT bureau)</td>\n<td>Shenzhen-registered entity; stacks with Hetao/Qianhai siting</td>\n<td>2025–2026 action plan</td>\n<td>Active <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"399\">[399]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>New Materials Big Data Center (matbd.cn)</td>\n<td>&quot;1+N&quot;: ≥30 nodes, ≥30 tools, ≥20 demos by 2027 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"400\">[400]</sup></td>\n<td>MIIT + MOF + NDA; main platform at USTB</td>\n<td>Node participation (science/industry/<strong>compute</strong> class); open beta portal</td>\n<td>Build-out to 2027; 2035 vision</td>\n<td>Beta live since 2025-05-06 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"400\">[400]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"401\">[401]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>CNMGE platform @ NSCC-Tianjin</td>\n<td>~50 materials codes; ~1,000 concurrent jobs <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"402\">[402]</sup></td>\n<td>NSCC-Tianjin (National Key R&amp;D Program)</td>\n<td>Rolling open research fund; free/discounted compute for external teams</td>\n<td>Rolling; 5th call 2025</td>\n<td>Active <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"402\">[402]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>15% CIT zones (Hainan FTP, Qianhai, Hetao)</td>\n<td>15% corporate income tax vs 25% standard <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"403\">[403]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"404\">[404]</sup></td>\n<td>MOF / STA</td>\n<td>WFOE with substantive operations; Hetao adds SAFE 科汇通 cross-border funding pilot</td>\n<td>Hainan to 2027-12-31; Hetao 2023–2027; Qianhai routinely extended</td>\n<td>Active <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"403\">[403]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"404\">[404]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Foreign R&amp;D-center measures (2023)</td>\n<td>Policy instrument</td>\n<td>State Council; MOFCOM/MOST</td>\n<td>Foreign-invested R&amp;D centers may undertake national S&amp;T projects; access national instruments and data <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"405\">[405]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"406\">[406]</sup></td>\n<td>In force since 2023</td>\n<td>Active <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"405\">[405]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"406\">[406]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>HKEX Chapter 18C</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>Hong Kong Exchanges</td>\n<td>Specialist-technology listing without a domestic VIE; XtalPi (2228.HK) precedent</td>\n<td>Rolling</td>\n<td>Proven since 2024-06 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"407\">[407]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Three patterns matter in this table. First, the instruments layer by stage: grants (NSFC), patient equity (guidance fund, AI fund), municipal top-ups (Beijing, Guangzhou, Shenzhen), in-kind compute and data (vouchers, matbd.cn, CNMGE), tax (15% CIT zones), and exit (18C) — a whole-chain architecture that mirrors the 全链条 language of the Recommendations. Second, the access-route column converges on one structural fact: every money route passes through a PRC-registered presence — a WFOE, a joint venture with a state lab or university, or a China-based principal investigator. Nothing on this table is receivable from abroad; I state that as a property of the system, not as advice. Third, the windows cluster: Hainan CIT runs to 2027-12-31, Hetao to 2027, Shenzhen's voucher plan through 2026, matbd.cn nodes by 2027, Beijing's plan to 2027. The on-ramps concentrate in the plan's first two years, which makes 2026–2027 the decision window. On confidence: the national instruments are documented in official texts, while the provincial fund figures and Shenzhen's voucher percentages are municipal disclosures whose disbursement pace is not public — I cite them as headline sizes <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"395\">[395]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"396\">[396]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"399\">[399]</sup>.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s16-4-2", "html": "<p>The Research Fund for International Scientists (RFIS) is the cleanest research on-ramp: three tiers paying direct costs of ¥200k, ¥400k, and ¥800k per year for one to two years — young scientists, excellent young scientists, senior scholars — covering the Engineering and Materials (E) and Interdisciplinary (T01–T04) departments, and designed to embed foreign principal investigators at Chinese institutions <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"392\">[392]</sup>. On the corporate side, the State Council's August 2023 foreign-investment measures (24 articles) encourage foreign-invested R&amp;D centers to undertake major national S&amp;T projects <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"405\">[405]</sup>, and the January 2023 MOFCOM/MOST measures add access to national large-scale instruments, S&amp;T reports and data, plus work-permit and residency facilitation <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"406\">[406]</sup>. The tax layer is dated: Hainan Free Trade Port's 15% corporate income tax for encouraged industries runs to 2027-12-31 (财税〔2025〕3号); Qianhai's regime (财税〔2021〕30号) has been routinely extended; Hetao's Shenzhen zone runs 2023–2027 (财税〔2024〕2号) and adds SAFE's 科汇通 pilot for cross-border research funding <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"403\">[403]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"404\">[404]</sup>. The capital-markets on-ramp is proven rather than theoretical: XtalPi listed under HKEX Chapter 18C in June 2024 (2228.HK) and reached its first adjusted half-year profit in H1 2025 on revenue of ¥517m, up 403.8% year-on-year — a route for a foreign-incorporated AI-for-science venture to list with China exposure and no domestic VIE <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"407\">[407]</sup>. The pattern I record, without prescription: the on-ramps are real, codified, and entity-bound, and each carries compliance obligations that §16.5 treats as first-class constraints.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s16-4-3", "html": "<p>Shenzhen's &quot;training-power vouchers&quot; (训力券) are the most directly monetizable compute subsidy I have found: up to 50% of a compute service contract, capped at ¥10m per award and raised to 60% for startups, inside a voucher budget of up to ¥500m per year — a municipal disclosure I cite as stated, since payout experience is not yet public <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"399\">[399]</sup>. At the national layer, the New Materials Big Data Center (工信部联原〔2024〕205号; MIIT, MOF, and the National Data Administration) is building a &quot;1+N&quot; architecture — one main platform at the University of Science and Technology Beijing plus N data nodes — with targets of at least 30 data-resource nodes, 30 algorithms and tools, and 20 data-empowered application demonstrations by 2027; nodes are classified science, industry, and <strong>compute</strong> — a compute-class node is the natural institutional role for a computational venture — and the public portal entered beta on 2025-05-06 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"400\">[400]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"401\">[401]</sup>. The China Materials Genome Engineering platform at NSCC-Tianjin complements it with roughly 50 integrated materials codes, about 1,000 concurrent jobs, and a rolling open research fund — fifth call in 2025 — that gives external teams free or discounted machine time: zero-capex DFT and MD throughput <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"402\">[402]</sup>.</p>\n<p>The domestic AI-for-science ecosystem is already funded and hiring. DP Technology closed a Series C above ¥800m in December 2025 at a valuation above ¥6bn — the largest domestic AI4S round — behind its DPA-2/OpenLAM universal interatomic potential covering more than 90 elements and the Bohrium compute cloud <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"408\">[408]</sup>. XtalPi operates robotic autonomous laboratories <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"407\">[407]</sup>. Songshan Lake Materials Laboratory has built the MatChat materials LLM, the Atomly inorganic database, the GPTFF universal force field, and a &quot;robot material scientist&quot; platform, and it hosts CAS's practical superconducting-film team <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"409\">[409]</sup>. The binding constraint sits above all of this: the US control timeline — October 2022, October 2023, April 2025 H20 licensing, August 2025 15%-revenue-share licenses, December 2025/January 2026 H200 case-by-case with a 25% surcharge — drove Nvidia's China frontier-training share &quot;from 95% to 0%,&quot; as its CEO put it, while domestic substitutes scale (Huawei Ascend 910C; Cambricon's H1 2025 revenue up 453% to ¥6.47bn) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"384\">[384]</sup>. My practical read: DFT/MD throughput screening runs well on NSCC CPU capacity and domestic accelerators; what the controls bind is foundation-scale pretraining. A venture that fine-tunes compact models rather than pretraining frontier ones sits below the constraint — which is the architecture this report recommends on scientific grounds anyway (Ch3).</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s16-4-4", "html": "<p>Fusion is the strongest single pull. Anhui's plan positions Hefei as a comprehensive national science center building the &quot;trillion-yuan fusion city&quot; (万亿聚变城) around BEST and CRAFT, with 聚变新能 (Fusion New Energy) as BEST's operating company and a target to complete the device in 2027 and demonstrate fusion power <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"389\">[389]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"321\">[321]</sup>. Hydrogen is quantified: the NDRC/NEA new-energy-system plan for the 15FYP period (2026-06-25) sets renewable hydrogen production of 2 Mt/yr by 2030 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"236\">[236]</sup>. High-temperature superconductors have a codified problem list: the CAS Institute of Physics's first REBCO strategic report (2026-01-26) frames &quot;ten key scientific and technological questions&quot; for tape scale-up — substrate strength, buffer layers, MOCVD multiphysics, cost — which Chapter 4 treats as a ready-made computational agenda <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"148\">[148]</sup>. Demand pull here is dated — 2027 for BEST, matbd.cn nodes, and Beijing's plan; 2030 for hydrogen and the AI+ penetration targets — and each date converts the fifteen-class list from rhetoric into a procurement calendar.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s16-5-1", "html": "<p>Five items, in the order I weight them. This subsection is compliance-oriented: it describes the surface so that any engagement design stays well inside it, and it offers no structuring advice.</p>\n<p><strong>First, 2026-11-10.</strong> The October 2025 MOFCOM package — including Announcement 61's extraterritorial 0.1% rule, modeled explicitly on the US foreign-direct-product rule — is suspended, not repealed, and the suspension lapses on 2026-11-10, inside the 15FYP's first year <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"388\">[388]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"243\">[243]</sup>. The April 2025 controls licensing seven medium and heavy rare earths (Announcement 18) were never suspended <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"242\">[242]</sup>, and the legal consensus reads the October measures as &quot;legally intact and can reactivate without new legislation&quot; <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"243\">[243]</sup>. Read from the Chinese side, this is coherence rather than contradiction: rare-earth functional materials are simultaneously an upgrade-tier priority (§16.3) and a control lever — the plan funds the capability while the control regime defends it. For any venture touching magnets, the date gates both markets at once (Ch9).</p>\n<p><strong>Second, the compute ratchet.</strong> Each license round since October 2022 has tightened and then partially reopened on revenue-share terms (§16.4.3); any GPU import into a China entity sits under US license conditions — a compliance workstream, not a procurement detail <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"384\">[384]</sup>.</p>\n<p><strong>Third, entity-list exposure.</strong> The United States added more than 140 Chinese semiconductor entities to its lists in December 2024 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"387\">[387]</sup>. I found no public record of DP Technology or XtalPi on BIS lists as of 2026-07-17 — a negative result I treat cautiously, since listings change without notice — and any China partner in defense-adjacent materials (aero-engine superalloys, ultra-high-purity metals for semiconductor equipment) raises diversion-risk screening on the US side <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"387\">[387]</sup>.</p>\n<p><strong>Fourth, materials-data governance.</strong> Materials data is a strategic resource under the 205号文 framework, with classified and graded (分类分级) security rules: cross-border transfer of project data from a China joint venture requires classified-data compliance, and the matbd.cn centralization may favor domestic nodes for the best datasets <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"400\">[400]</sup>.</p>\n<p><strong>Fifth, IP and publication asymmetry.</strong> National programs typically require China-side or joint IP ownership; the 205号文 promises strengthened data security and IP protection, but enforcement in joint-venture settings is contract-dependent <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"400\">[400]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"406\">[406]</sup>.</p>\n<p>My posture follows from the surface, not around it: export-control and data-classification counsel sign off before any China commitment, and every engagement uses the codified on-ramps of §16.4.2 exactly as written.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s16-5-2", "html": "<p>The mirror of §16.2 and the on-ramps of §16.4 say dual alignment is possible: both systems fund the same simulation-hard classes, and China has codified the routes — RFIS tiers, joint funds, the 2023 R&amp;D-center measures, the 15% CIT zones, Chapter 18C — through which even a one-person venture can engage without incumbency. The gates of §16.5.1 say the alignment is time-gated: the codified windows cluster inside the plan's first two years, and above all of them sits one date. 2026-11-10 is the date I watch most closely in this report's entire policy map. If the October-package suspension is extended or replaced, the on-ramps of Table 16.3 remain open in fact as well as on paper, and a China research presence becomes a 2027 decision. If it lapses, rare-earth work reprices overnight on both sides, the control regimes ratchet in both directions, and the compliance surface — not science, not money — decides what a foreign entity may touch. My sequencing follows that asymmetry: the US-side stack of Chapter 17 comes first, because its windows open earlier and its gates are eligibility gates; the China-side engagement is designed so that nothing in it depends on the suspension being renewed. Either way, the fifteen named classes will be funded, staffed, and procured — and I intend to be the independent lab selling verified simulation into them, on both sides of the mirror, before the date decides for me.</p>\n" },
]
